<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-01-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-01-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="484" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d484">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 738.3915/92.]</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister to
                                    Haiti</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-01-08">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 8, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>I am assured by the President of Haiti that on December 23, 1911, he
                            ordered the frontier authorities to prevent Dominican revolutionists
                            from entering Haitian territory.<note n="2" xml:id="d484fn2">see <ref target="frus1911#pg_166">For. Rel., 1911, p. 166</ref>.</note>
                            The Haitian authorities, says the President, are greatly hampered by
                            lack of support by the Dominican authorities on the frontier; prior to
                            the death of President Cáceres<note n="3" xml:id="d484fn3">Nov. 20,
                                1911; see <ref target="frus1911#pg_174">For. Rel., 1911, p.
                                    174</ref>.</note> they acted in conjunction with the Haitian
                            authorities, but since then they have been inactive.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Furniss</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>